<div class="container">
  <hr>
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-12">
      <h3><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign"></span> How to change the domain of an application</h3>
      <div class="alert alert-info text-center" role="alert">
        Wordpress stores the absolute path of site URL (“siteurl”) and the home URL (“homeurl”) in the database. If you transfer your Wordpress site from localhost to server or if you change the domain, the site will not load or point to the wrong address! You need to execute some queries in the database. These queries are generated by our page. This tip was copied from the article in Portuguese <a href='http://desenvolvimentoparaweb.com/wordpress/15-comandos-sql-wordpress/'>here</a>.
      </div>
      <form action="/" method="post">
          <div class="form-group">
            <label for="oldDomain">Enter the old domain:</label>
            <input type="text" name="oldDomain">
            <p class="help-block">Enter the old domain with a http:// or https://</p>
          </div>
          <div class="form-group">
            <label for="newDomain">Enter the new domain:</label>
            <input type="text" name="newDomain">
            <p class="help-block">Enter the new domain with a http:// or https://</p>
          </div>
          
          <button type="submit" class="btn btn-lg btn-primary" >Submit</button>
      </form>
    </div>
    <%if (oldDomain) { %>
    <div class="col-md-12">
      <h3><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-info-sign"></span> Result</h3>
      <% include ../partials/queries.ejs %>
    </div>
    <% } %>

    <div class="alert alert-info text-center" role="alert">
        Layout stolen from the <a href="https://github.com/heroku/node-js-getting-started">Node.js Heroku sample application </a>
    </div>

</body>
</html>
